 break them down by type so you know what you&rsquo;re looking at in listings &mdash; and what suits you.</p><p>Important: in Vietnam, engine size <b>up to 50cc</b> is the category that needs <b>no licence</b> &mdash; which is why tourists and long-stayers love it. More on that in <a href="prava-50cc-en.html">&ldquo;Do you need a licence for a 50cc&rdquo;</a>.</p><h2>1. Automatic scooters (xe ga)</h2><figure><img src="img/article/type-scooter.jpg" alt="Automatic scooter - twist the throttle and go, no gears" loading="lazy"><figcaption>Automatic scooter - twist the throttle and go, no gears</figcaption></figure><p>The most popular and simplest type &mdash; <b>xe ga</b> in Vietnamese. No gears: twist the throttle and ride. Under the seat there&rsquo;s roomy storage for a helmet and shopping. Perfect for beginners, city riding and short trips.</p><p>Typical models in this size: Honda Vision, Honda Scoopy and local scooters in the same format. Pros &mdash; simplicity and comfort. Con &mdash; the automatic transmission (CVT) is a bit pricier to repair than a manual.</p><h2>2. Vespa-style retro scooters</h2><figure><img src="img/article/type-vespa.jpg" alt="A Vespa-style retro scooter - stylish and photogenic" loading="lazy"><figcaption>A Vespa-style retro scooter - stylish and photogenic</figcaption></figure><p>Also automatic, but with rounded vintage styling inspired by the classic Vespa. Vietnam has plenty &mdash; local brands (Nioshima, Elegant and others) make these 50s affordable. People buy them for the look: they&rsquo;re photogenic, great against the sea, and hold their value on resale.</p><p>Mechanically they&rsquo;re the same easy twist-and-go scooters. The difference is mostly the styling and riding position. A great pick if you want more than just transport.</p><h2>3. Honda Cub and retro step-throughs (xe so cong)</h2><figure><img src="img/article/type-cub.jpg" alt="Honda Cub - the iconic Vietnamese bike with an immortal engine" loading="lazy"><figcaption>Honda Cub - the iconic Vietnamese bike with an immortal engine</figcaption></figure><p>A legend of Vietnamese roads. The <b>Honda Cub</b> and similar curved-frame step-throughs are semi-automatic: they have gears, but the clutch is automatic &mdash; no lever to squeeze. The engine is nearly indestructible, repairs cost pennies, and many people love the vintage look more than any new scooter.</p><p>You choose this for reliability and character. It&rsquo;s slightly trickier than a full auto (you shift gears with your foot), but you get used to it in a day.</p><h2>4. Manual bikes - Honda Wave and underbones (xe so)</h2><figure><img src="img/article/type-wave.jpg" alt="Honda Wave - a manual bike with gears, cheap to maintain" loading="lazy"><figcaption>Honda Wave - a manual bike with gears, cheap to maintain</figcaption></figure><p>These are <b>xe so</b> &mdash; bikes with manual gear shifting and a sportier stance. The classic is the Honda Wave and similar underbones. Cheapest to maintain, tough and long-lived. Loved by people staying in Vietnam long-term who want the most reliable, repairable ride.</p><p>The downside for beginners: you shift gears manually (with your foot) and feel the clutch. If you&rsquo;ve never ridden a manual, start with an automatic and get a Wave later.</p><h2>How to know it&rsquo;s really 50cc</h2><p>Not everything called a &ldquo;50&rdquo; really is 50cc &mdash; a 50cc and a 110cc can look identical. The only reliable way is the <b>papers</b> (ca vet) stating the engine size, plus checking the engine number. That&rsquo;s exactly why we only sell bikes with <b>clean papers, checked against the police database</b> &mdash; so &ldquo;no licence&rdquo; is the truth, not a surprise with the police.</p><h2>What to choose</h2><ul><li><b>Beginner / short trip:</b> automatic scooter (xe ga).</li><li><b>Want style:</b> a Vespa-style retro.</li><li><b>Reliability and character:</b> Honda Cub.</li><li><b>Staying long, value cheap repairs:</b> Honda Wave (manual).</li></ul><p>How to pick a specific bike and what to check when buying &mdash; see <a href="vybor-baika-50cc-en.html">&ldquo;How to choose your first 50cc&rdquo;</a>. How to care for it in a hot climate &mdash; see <a href="uhod-za-baikom-en.html">&ldquo;Scooter care&rdquo;</a>.</p><p style="margin-top:24px"><a href="catalog-en.html" class="btn btn-wa">See bikes in stock &rarr;</a> <a href="kak-kupit-en.html" class="btn btn-tg" style="margin-left:8px">How to buy &rarr;</a></p></div></section><footer><div class="wrap"><div class="fgrid"><div><h4>50cc bikes in Nha Trang</h4><p>Affordable, turnkey 50cc bikes in Nha Trang — serviced, washed, with papers. No licence needed: land, buy, ride.</p><div class="pay"><span>₫ VND</span><span>$ USD</span><span>USDT</span><span>Cash</span></div></div><div><h4>Menu</h4><a href="catalog-en.html">Catalog</a><a href="vykup-en.html">How it works</a><a href="kak-kupit-en.html">How to buy</a><a href="blog-en.html">Articles</a><a href="o-nas-en.html">About</a></div><div><h4>Contacts</h4><a href="https://wa.me/84386818874">WhatsApp</a><a href="https://t.me/babaskin_o">Telegram</a><a href="https://instagram.com/bike50cc_nha_trang">Instagram</a><a href="https://maps.app.goo.gl/jsxikqy9AZMNtmAE6" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Google Maps</a><p>Nha Trang · daily</p></div></div><div class="copy">© 2026 50cc bikes in Nha Trang. All rights reserved.</div></div></footer></body></html>